{{Infobox person | name = Carl Adolf Seebold | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = 1873 | birth_place = [[Zürich]], Switzerland | death_date = 1951 | death_place = [[Worthing]], [[West Sussex]], England | occupation = [[Impresario]] | main interests = | spouse = Married | salary = | URL = | title = }}
'''Carl Adolf Seebold''' (1873–1951) was a [[Swiss people|Swiss]] impresario who commissioned and ran the [[Dome Cinema]] in the English coastal town of [[Worthing]] in [[West Sussex]].
Swiss-born Seebold was the son of a rope manufacturer from [[Zürich]].<ref name="SWDome"/> The father fell on hard times and turned to entertainment, playing the guitar and singing, to support a large family of nine sons and four daughters.<ref name="SWDome"/> A violinist, Seebold became leader of his family's Swiss band, the [[Chamonix|Chamounix]] Orchestra in 1897.<ref name="MEW">Elleray, D. Robert (1998). A Millennium Encyclopaedia of Worthing History. Worthing: Optimus Books. {{ISBN|0-9533132-0-4}}</ref> The Orchestra toured widely and were invited to play before many of the royal households of Europe.<ref name="SWDome"/> They were invited to England by Sir [[Alfred Butt]], appearing at [[The Crystal Palace]], [[Queen's Hall]] and various resorts, including Worthing.<ref name="MEW"/>
Between 1900 and 1903, Seebold and his family had been lessees at [[Southend Pier]].<ref name="MEW"/><ref name="SOOT">{{Cite web|url=http://archive.theargus.co.uk/2003/2/19/140052.html/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070813052636/http://archive.theargus.co.uk/2003/2/19/140052.html/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=13 August 2007 |title=Signs of Our Times |date=19 February 2003 |publisher=The Argus newspaper |accessdate=9 February 2010 }}</ref>
In October 1904, Seebold settled in Worthing, and was the proprietor of the town's New Theatre Royal in Bath Place.<ref name="SWDome">{{Cite web|url=http://www.worthingdomecinema.com/key.php#1/|title=The Saving of Worthing Dome|date=2005–2008|publisher=Worthing Dome Cinema|accessdate=9 February 2010}}</ref><ref name="MEW"/> He lived at Bedford House, on the town's seafront. In 1909 Seebold built the entertainment centre known as the ''Kursaal'' (later the Dome) in the lawns of Bedford House.<ref name="MEW"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worthingdome.com/history.html|title=History of The Worthing Dome|website=www.worthingdome.com|access-date=2017-06-07|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131210050054/http://worthingdome.com/history.html|archivedate=10 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Seebold later moved out of Bedford House to 52 Richmond Road in Worthing.<ref name="MEW"/>
In 1924, Seebold opened the Rivoli cinema, also in [[Worthing]] and in 1926 he acquired a rival cinema, the [[Connaught Theatre|Picturedrome]].<ref name="VCH18225">{{Cite web|url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/Sussex/vol6/pp105-108|title=A History of the County of Sussex: Volume 6 Part 1: Bramber Rape (Southern Part). Worthing: Social and Cultural Activities|last=Salzman|first=L. F. (ed)|year=1980|work=[[Victoria County History]] of Sussex|publisher=British History Online|pages=105–108|accessdate=2009-12-07}}</ref> In 1949, Seebold founded The Rivoli and Dome Ltd and married for a second time.
Seebold died in 1951.
